{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"41e8fe0a-3b18-4eda-bdae-97dc89c21f20","content":"The project doesn't exist in the working directory, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run` pointing at your `.csproj`.\n- For a **published** build, replace with `\"command\": \"path/to/MyMcpServer\"` and remove the args.\n- If your server uses **SSE/HTTP** transport instead, use `\"type\": \"sse\"` with a `\"url\"` field.\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot chat in agent mode — VS Code will auto-discover and start the server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"67891240-c1e1-4cf2-98ec-c3b7617cefe9","outputTokens":280,"requestId":"3C0D:2310B5:202179F:2407354:69E81CDB"},"id":"eeac91dc-cf61-4ea0-86ca-e2b053fd54fd","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:57:07.768Z","parentId":"63cdb78e-0098-4d9c-b26e-80f64121933a"}
